nteenth century? What if “the human” is at once embedded and embodied in, evolving with, and de-centered amid a weird tangle of animals, environments, and vital materiality? Seeking those patterns of thought and practice, contributors to this collection focus on moments wherein Renaissance humanism looks retrospectively like an uncanny “contemporary”—and ally—of twenty-first-century critical posthumanism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHumanism. 0aHumanities. 0aPost-postmodernism. 0aRenaissance. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aAnimal Studies.  aEcology.  aHuman.  aMilton.  aPosthumanism.  aRabelais.  aRenaissance Humanism.  aShakespeare.  aTitian.1 aBovilsky, Lara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampana, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampana, Joseph, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCampbell, Stephen J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDugan, Holly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFudge, Erica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGouwens, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaisano, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaisano, Scott, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNardizzi, Vin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoof, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolfthal, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYates, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham Universi